            "answer_text": "The coldest documented temperature ever reached was about 100 trillionths of a degree above absolute zero\u2014at the Helsinki University of Technology on August 12, 2000 by supercoooling a microscopic granule of rhodium using a process of concentrated adiabatic nuclear demagnetization. Fabrice Neyret makes a crucial observation. Everything atomic or otherwise is a system of flux that tends toward a theoretic norm. In the above referenced rhodium nuclei, the massive flux within them never even diminished at trillionths of a degree above zero-K, proving conclusively that irrespective of the bounds of \u201ctemperature\u201d and \u201celectromagnetism\u201d there are incomprehensibly vast forces at work that are yet centuries beyond our current grasp. ",
