            "author_info": {
                "name": "Shawn McCaslin",
                "href": "/profile/Shawn-McCaslin"
            },
            "answer_text": "For a gas to be at zero Kelvin, the particles in the gas must have no kinetic energy; i.e., they must be perfectly stationary. One way to achieve this for a particular particle is to use it as the reference frame; thus, it, by definition, is at zero Kelvin. You can also say that a particle is perfectly still for a single instant when it reverses direction, say, due to force from a magnetic or electric field. But broadly speaking, physics never measures anything with perfect precision; even fundamental physical constants are known only to parts per trillion at best. For example, it seems reasonable to assume that all electrons are identical, but electron mass can be measured to be uniform only to about 10 ppb. Thus, even if you had achieved zero Kelvin with a particular sample, you cannot know. ",
