            "author_info": {
                "name": "B.T. Yang",
                "href": "/profile/B-T-Yang"
            },
            "answer_text": "Many \u201ctheoretic values\u201d in math and sciences can never be reached but remain extremely useful in construct a mathematical model without having to deal with many distracting details: absolute zero temperature, delta function, singularity, and infinity. In this particular case, one can only achieve absolute zero temperature if infinite energy is applied\u2014so you can see the irony. And don\u2019t forget about space travel at the speed of light too\u2026. ",
            "date": "Answered October 26, 2017",
            "views": "291",
            "upvotes": "0"
