        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "David Rosen",
                "href": "/profile/David-Rosen-52"
            },
            "answer_text": "It makes it a \u2018limiting case\u2019, not a \u2018theoretical temperature\u2019. It can\u2019 be achieved, but it can be approached as close as one wants. The temperature in a closed system can asymptotically approach absolute zero in an infinite number of steps. This means that one can achieve any temperature above absolute zero by some mechanical process with a finite number of steps. However, the lower the temperature the more steps are needed. The idea of infinitesimal is critical to understanding limiting cases. Basically, all of physics and chemistry involves \u2018limiting cases\u2019. Read \u2018Infinitesimals: The History of a Dangerous Idea\u2019 by Amir Alexander. ",
